      <span class="key-stat-num">347%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">A 2023 JAMA study found that some melatonin gummies contained up to <strong>347% of their labeled dose</strong>. This means a product claiming 5mg could actually deliver 17mg — a massive hormonal overdose that far exceeds the physiological range of 0.3-0.5mg.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The problem with melatonin extends beyond dosing inconsistency. Melatonin is a hormone, not a vitamin. It is produced by the pineal gland as a signal to initiate sleep — and when you introduce it externally at supraphysiological doses night after night, you risk disrupting your body's endogenous production. The result for many users is a cycle of dependency where they cannot fall asleep without the supplement, even though it was never intended for long-term use.</p>

